Lastly, the component name will follow the camel case methodology: customFieldName.

For example:

·      Apex Class: WESAL_cls_apexName
·      LWC: WESER_lwc_componentName
·      RecordType: WERFEN_rt_recordTypeName

Other Nomenclatures
Labels
All labels must begin with an uppercase letter and continue in lowercase. For example: Custom field

List View
These components must use the application prefix, for example: WESAL_nameOfTheListView

Home Pages
These components must use the application prefix, for example: WESAL_nameOfTheHomePage

Documents
These components must use the application prefix, for example: WESAL_nameOfDocument

Letterhead
These components must use the application prefix, for example: WESAL_nameOfLetterHead

Apex Classes
For the different Apex class types, we will also use a special naming convention by means of suffixes.

For example, starting from a base Apex class: WESAL_cls_nameApexClass

Test: WESAL_cls_nameApexClass_test
Utils: WESAL_cls_nameApexClass_utils
Batch: WESAL_cls_nameApexClass_batch
Scheduled: WESAL_cls_nameApexClass_sch
Queueable: WESAL_cls_nameApexClass_queue
Apex Variables
Use descriptive names for variables and avoid single‑letter names such as Integer a or String c, except when used as counters or control variables.

Lists must begin with lst (e.g., lstCustomers).
Maps must begin with map (e.g., mapDistributors).
Sets must begin with set (e.g., setContacts).
Apex Constants
Constants must be written in uppercase letters using an underscore _ as a separator: For example: NAME_EXAMPLE

Apex Triggers
Triggers will be unique and centralized per object, invoking handler‑type classes to manage the required logic. This approach allows, for example, the use of custom settings to enable or disable different handlers within a trigger without affecting the behavior of the remaining logic.

For example: WERFEN_trg_Account & WESAL_cls_handlerAccountCustomers
